title:
If Elon were to create his party in Indonesia, I believe it could enter the "Congress", because smaller parties can gain seats there as long as they meet the 4% parliamentary threshold.

Let’s assume the “No Label” party, chosen by the American people, managed to gather around 6 million votes across all states, that would be enough for them to immediately compete in Congress.

But what if they get less than 4%?
Some of them would still win regional-level seats, like in provincial or city/district councils, as long as they win in their local areas (they don’t need to win the entire state).

Now, when we’re talking about America, it’s almost impossible for a new party to break the dominance of the two major parties. Congress is completely dominated by these two camps, and they have no interest in sharing power with smaller parties that might actually offer better ideals or fresh solutions.

That’s why, no matter who wins, they win everything. And whoever loses, loses everything.
Small parties are left with no space to move, let alone to contribute or push for real change from the inside.

You want change, right? Then change the system, not just create a new party.
But, if building a new party can be your way to change the system from within, then so be it.
Alright, that’s just my perspective on Elon wanting to start his own party.

And I also realize, it’s nearly impossible for Elon to actually pull it off.

title: Setting aside all the factors that go into selection for missions to Mars, I wonder if this voyage marks the first time a civilization is established without a generational warrior/hunter class. My 430am logic assumes just about all established societies gained establishment through conflicting wills between peoples. The society with the more talented and/or larger warrior class dominates an area, a leader from among that warrior class is inevitably selected (I imagine with the respect and loyalty of said warrior class). From there, other individuals are chosen as "Management," infrastructure and community obligations are set up and organized. At some point the scientists, the artisans, and the philosophers establish themselves within the society. In the case of the SpaceX mission, a new society is formed not through conquest, but through science, innovation, and the power of nerds. Security, law enforcement, and defense may take a back seat for the first time in human history. However, humans are humans. At (X) number of people, societal flaws such as thievery, corruption, and lust for power will act as forcing functions for the establishment of a police/security/military class. Does this new paradigm simply prolong a return to the familiar or do scientists, engineers, and philosophers reach levels of cultural regard typically reserved for celebrities, lawyers, and politicians?

Not as people, not as human beings.
Not so simply deduced through simple and limited observation.
